  "tutorial/extra-models::section-0004": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0004",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0003",
    "level": 4,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Pydantic's .model_dump()",
    "anchor_id": "pydantics-model-dump",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#pydantics-model-dump",
    "section_text": "user_in is a Pydantic model of class UserIn .\n\nPydantic models have a .model_dump() method that returns a dict with the model's data.\n\nSo, if we create a Pydantic object user_in like:\n\nand then we call:\n\nwe now have a dict with the data in the variable user_dict (it's a dict instead of a Pydantic model object).\n\nAnd if we call:\n\nwe would get a Python dict with:",
    "section_inline_code": [
      ".model_dump()",
      "user_in",
      "UserIn",
      "dict",
      "user_dict"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "user_in = UserIn(username=\"john\", password=\"secret\", email=\"john.doe@example.com\")",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0004",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#pydantics-model-dump"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "user_dict = user_in.model_dump()",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0004",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#pydantics-model-dump"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "print(user_dict)",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0004",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#pydantics-model-dump"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "{\n    'username': 'john',\n    'password': 'secret',\n    'email': 'john.doe@example.com',\n    'full_name': None,\n}",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0004",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#pydantics-model-dump"
      }
    ]
  },
  "tutorial/extra-models::section-0005": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0005",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0003",
    "level": 4,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Unpacking a dict",
    "anchor_id": "unpacking-a-dict",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#unpacking-a-dict",
    "section_text": "If we take a dict like user_dict and pass it to a function (or class) with **user_dict , Python will \"unpack\" it. It will pass the keys and values of the user_dict directly as key-value arguments.\n\nSo, continuing with the user_dict from above, writing:\n\nwould result in something equivalent to:\n\nOr more exactly, using user_dict directly, with whatever contents it might have in the future:",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "dict",
      "user_dict",
      "**user_dict"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "UserInDB(**user_dict)",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0005",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#unpacking-a-dict"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "UserInDB(\n    username=\"john\",\n    password=\"secret\",\n    email=\"john.doe@example.com\",\n    full_name=None,\n)",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0005",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#unpacking-a-dict"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "UserInDB(\n    username = user_dict[\"username\"],\n    password = user_dict[\"password\"],\n    email = user_dict[\"email\"],\n    full_name = user_dict[\"full_name\"],\n)",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0005",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#unpacking-a-dict"
      }
    ]
  },
  "tutorial/extra-models::section-0006": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0006",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0003",
    "level": 4,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "A Pydantic model from the contents of another",
    "anchor_id": "a-pydantic-model-from-the-contents-of-another",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#a-pydantic-model-from-the-contents-of-another",
    "section_text": "As in the example above we got user_dict from user_in.model_dump() , this code:\n\nwould be equivalent to:\n\n...because user_in.model_dump() is a dict , and then we make Python \"unpack\" it by passing it to UserInDB prefixed with ** .\n\nSo, we get a Pydantic model from the data in another Pydantic model.",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "user_dict",
      "user_in.model_dump()",
      "dict",
      "UserInDB",
      "**"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "user_dict = user_in.model_dump()\nUserInDB(**user_dict)",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0006",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#a-pydantic-model-from-the-contents-of-another"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "UserInDB(**user_in.model_dump())",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0006",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#a-pydantic-model-from-the-contents-of-another"
      }
    ]
  },
  "tutorial/extra-models::section-0007": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0007",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0003",
    "level": 4,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Unpacking a dict and extra keywords",
    "anchor_id": "unpacking-a-dict-and-extra-keywords",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#unpacking-a-dict-and-extra-keywords",
    "section_text": "And then adding the extra keyword argument hashed_password=hashed_password , like in:\n\n...ends up being like:",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "dict",
      "hashed_password=hashed_password"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "UserInDB(**user_in.model_dump(), hashed_password=hashed_password)",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0007",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#unpacking-a-dict-and-extra-keywords"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "UserInDB(\n    username = user_dict[\"username\"],\n    password = user_dict[\"password\"],\n    email = user_dict[\"email\"],\n    full_name = user_dict[\"full_name\"],\n    hashed_password = hashed_password,\n)",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0007",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#unpacking-a-dict-and-extra-keywords"
      }
    ]
  },
  "tutorial/extra-models::section-0008": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0008",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Reduce duplication",
    "anchor_id": "reduce-duplication",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#reduce-duplication",
    "section_text": "Reducing code duplication is one of the core ideas in FastAPI .\n\nAs code duplication increments the chances of bugs, security issues, code desynchronization issues (when you update in one place but not in the others), etc.\n\nAnd these models are all sharing a lot of the data and duplicating attribute names and types.\n\nWe could do better.\n\nWe can declare a UserBase model that serves as a base for our other models. And then we can make subclasses of that model that inherit its attributes (type declarations, validation, etc).\n\nAll the data conversion, validation, documentation, etc. will still work as normally.\n\nThat way, we can declare just the differences between the models (with plaintext password , with hashed_password and without password):",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "UserBase",
      "password",
      "hashed_password"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [
      {
        "type": "code_ref",
        "path": "../../docs_src/extra_models/tutorial002_py310.py",
        "highlight_lines": [
          7,
          13,
          14,
          17,
          18,
          21,
          22
        ],
        "raw": "{* ../../docs_src/extra_models/tutorial002_py310.py hl[7,13:14,17:18,21:22] *}",
        "section_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0008",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#reduce-duplication"
      }
    ],
    "code_blocks": []
  },
  "tutorial/extra-models::section-0009": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0009",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/extra-models::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Union or anyOf",
    "anchor_id": "union-or-anyof",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#union-or-anyof",
    "section_text": "You can declare a response to be the Union of two or more types, that means, that the response would be any of them.\n\nIt will be defined in OpenAPI with anyOf .\n\nTo do that, use the standard Python type hint typing.Union :",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "Union",
      "anyOf",
      "typing.Union"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [
      {
        "type": "code_ref",
        "path": "../../docs_src/extra_models/tutorial003_py310.py",
        "highlight_lines": [
          1,
          14,
